        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To optimize the probability for detecting the [CII] 158 micron line in emission, we require DLA targets with high values of l_c, and with redshifts shifting 158 micron into frequency bands accessible with ALMA. Because of the correlation found between l_c and SFR, and between SFR and galaxy mass [27],[28], we focus on “high-peak” DLAs exhibiting evidence for significant SFRs. In principle, the 158 micron transition can be detected in three main redshift windows: z=[1.7,2.0], accessible with band 9,  z=[2.8,3.9] accessible with band 8, and z=[4.2,4.8], accessible with band 7. While there are  “high-peak” DLAs within all redshift windows, so far the only objects exhibiting independent evidence for star formation are “high-peak” DLAs found at the lower redshifts. Therefore, despite the higher sensitivity of band 7 and 8, we have selected our targets from the lower redshift window accessible with band 9.

The primary beam at this frequency is ~9 arcsec, much larger than the expected extent of the emission region. Therefore, we will use a single pointing only. The accurate redshift of our target is  z=1.7947 which implies that the [CII] emission is expected at 680.0 GHz.

We plan to observe the [CII] line in the Upper Side Band. The first and second basebands will be tuned 850MHz above and below the expected frequency of the [CII] line. This way, they overlap with 0.3 GHz so as to provide a contiguous bandwidth of 3.5 GHz, corresponding to ~1650 km/s, which is sufficient for an accurate continuum subtraction. Using the low resolution TDM mode, dual polarization, this will provide a channel width of ~14 km/s. This is sufficient to spectrally resolve the emission lines, which have expected widths of approximately 200 km/s. To optimize the signal-to-noise ratio, we will spectrally smooth the data to 100 to 200 MHz, depending on the profile width. 

The peak flux densities predicted in the scientific justification is a lower limit of 8 mJy over 200 km/s (the expected integrated flux is greater than 1.6 Jy km/s). In order to detect this line at greater than the 5 sigma level, we aim to reach an r.m.s. noise level of 1.5 mJy per 200 MHz (88 km/s), which for target DLA 1313+14 should be reached in 1.26 hrs which with overhead will be 3.31 hours.

The remaining two basebands will be used for making a continuum map. The combined usable bandwidth for making a continuum map is  6.5 GHz (excluding the band edges and 500 MHz around the emission line), implying that we will reach a 1 sigma continuum sensitivity of 0.245 mJy. The most compact configuration will be used, which will result in a spatial resolution of ~0.4 arcsec, using natural weighting. With more extended configurations we expect to spatially overresolve the emission and lose power on the longer baselines.

We performed simulations with the simobserve task in CASA to estimate the detectability of our targets. Specifically, we convolved a simulated galaxy [29] with similar properties as the proposed DLA (Fig. 4a) with the ALMA beam. Assuming the configurations defined above, we show the expected channel map for the target in Figures 4b. The channel maps are separated by 200MHz, with contour levels at 2 and 5 sigma. The galaxy is detectable at greater than the 5 sigma confidence level in at least two independent user smoothed 200 MHz channels. Also, based on these simulations, we may be able to just resolve the emission, since 0.4 arcsec corresponds to ~4 kpc.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
